25|$|The current {{federal income}} tax law allows {{individuals}} to deduct the <b>home</b> <b>mortgage</b> interest costs from taxable income (unless the taxpayer {{is subject to the}} Alternative Minimum Tax). <b>Home</b> <b>mortgage</b> interest {{is one of the few}} personal expenditures that is treated in this manner. Someone paying a 25% income tax rate would receive $250 back from the government for $1,000 expended in <b>home</b> <b>mortgage</b> interest. While there is no deduction for payroll taxes and most do not itemize the income tax deduction for full benefit, this preferential treatment of mortgage interest encourages households to spend relatively more of their income on housing than would otherwise be the case.|$|E
